Problem Statement
Wikipedia is one of the largest structured text corpora available, but its raw content is noisy and difficult to use directly for NLP tasks. This project explores natural language processing techniques — including text extraction, frequency analysis, and topic modeling — applied to Wikipedia article data.
Dataset Source
Wikipedia article content fetched via the Wikipedia API or a pre-downloaded dump. Data covers a range of article topics used to demonstrate NLP pipeline steps.
Approach

Article parsing and cleaning (stripping markup, handling special characters).
Word frequency and n-gram analysis.
TF-IDF vectorization for document representation.
Topic modeling (LDA or similar) to identify latent themes across articles.
Named entity recognition (NER) to extract people, places, and organizations.

Key Findings

Wikipedia articles cluster meaningfully by topic even without supervision, validating the quality of TF-IDF and LDA representations.
Stop word removal and lemmatization are critical preprocessing steps for clean topic separation.
NER surface-level accuracy is high on well-structured Wikipedia text compared to informal corpora.
